items.content_text: Good time of the spring to find these plants - most were in flower or at least had lots of buds.

items.title: Acacia aspera subsp. parviceps, Calomela acaciae
items.content_text: Looked at a lot of plants today and found only four of the beetles.

items.content_text: Even the young plants are showing buds and flowers.

items.title: Astrotricha ledifolia s.s.
items.content_text: Just getting started with buds but plants observed in the area have more leaves than last year.

items.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
items.content_text: This white with pink tinged flowering bush is typical of what is occurring this spring.

items.title: Euryomyrtus ramosissima subsp. ramosissima
items.content_text: Great flowering after good winter rains.

items.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
items.content_text: This very pink flowering plant is one amongst the many white/pinkish flowering specimens.

items.title: Prostanthera decussata
items.content_text: First flowers for the season - many buds.

items.title: Pomaderris elliptica var. elliptica
items.content_text: I waited and waited for this to flower and missed it by that much.

items.title: Leionema lamprophyllum subsp. obovatum
items.content_text: This shrub had finished flowering but the remnants of the flowers made a beautiful spectacle.

items.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
items.content_text: Young plant on the road edge

items.title: Phyllanthus hirtellus
items.content_text: Many of the plants had been foraged heavily.

items.title: Acacia aspera subsp. parviceps
items.content_text: Area had been cleared - plants developing into substantial shrubs and flowering very well.

items.title: Pultenaea daltonii
items.content_text: Plants growing among other shrubs have some protection for the herbivores allowing for more leaves and healthier plants.

items.title: Pultenaea daltonii
items.content_text: Many plants in the area have been heavily foraged and some have almost no leaves left.

items.title: Grevillea chrysophaea
items.content_text: Very small plant but still producing a flower

items.title: Bossiaea obcordata
items.content_text: First flower I have seen this season - plants are carrying lots of buds.

items.title: Olearia minor
items.content_text: This plant had a caterpillar which was feeding on the flower.

items.title: Boronia anemonifolia subsp. anemonifolia
items.content_text: The four or five plants found were very small having been eaten by herbivores (rabbits, wallabies or both) extensively.

items.title: Hibbertia exutiacies
items.content_text: Small shrub - all plants have been heavily grazed.  These plants have the propensity to grow amongst the mosses.

items.title: Grevillea steiglitziana
items.content_text: This grevillea is a low spreading shrub with shiny, lightly toothed, holly-like leaves and bright red toothbrush flowers.  It is found in Victoria, mostly confined to the Brisbane Ranges between Geelong & Bacchus marsh.  Grows in dry, open eucalypt forest
